# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: atomic-clock
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The **12-hour clock** is a time convention in which the 24 hours of the day are divided into two periods: **a.m.** (from Latin ***ante meridiem***, translating to "before midday") and **p.m.** (from Latin ***post meridiem***, translating to "after midday").
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock has been developed since the second millennium BC and reached its modern form in the 16th century.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour time convention is common in several English-speaking nations and former British colonies, as well as a few other countries.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] In English-speaking countries: "12 p.m." usually indicates noon, while "12 a.m." means midnight, but the reverse convention has also been used (see § Confusion at noon and midnight).
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The natural day-and-night division of a calendar day forms the fundamental basis as to why each day is split into two cycles.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Originally there were two cycles: one cycle which could be tracked by the position of the Sun (day), followed by one cycle which could be tracked by the Moon and stars (night).
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] This eventually evolved into the two 12-hour periods which are used today, one called "a.m." starting at midnight and another called "p.m." starting at noon.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock can be traced back as far as Mesopotamia and ancient Egypt.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Both an Egyptian sundial for daytime use and an Egyptian water clock for night-time use were found in the tomb of Pharaoh Amenhotep I.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] 1500 BC, these clocks divided their respective times of use into 12 hours each.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The ancient Romans also used a 12-hour clock: daylight and nighttime were each divided into 12 equal intervals (of varying duration according to the season).
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The nighttime hours were grouped into four *watches* (*vigiliae*).
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The first mechanical clocks in the 14th century, if they had dials at all, showed all 24 hours using the 24-hour analog dial, influenced by astronomers' familiarity with the astrolabe and sundial and by their desire to model the Earth's apparent motion around the Sun.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] In Northern Europe these dials generally used the 12-hour numbering scheme in Roman numerals but showed both *a.m.* and *p.m.* periods in sequence.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] This is known as the double-XII system and can be seen on many surviving clock faces, such as those at Wells and Exeter.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Elsewhere in Europe, numbering was more likely to be based on the 24-hour system (I to XXIV).
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock was used throughout the British Empire.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] During the 15th and 16th centuries, the 12-hour analog dial and time system gradually became established as standard throughout Northern Europe for general public use.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The 24-hour analog dial was reserved for more specialized applications, such as astronomical clocks and chronometers.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Most analog clocks and watches today use the 12-hour dial, on which the shorter hour hand rotates once every 12 hours and twice in one day.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Some analog clock dials have an inner ring of numbers along with the standard 1-to-12 numbered ring.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The number 12 is paired either with a 00 or a 24, while the numbers 1 through 11 are paired with the numbers 13 through 23, respectively.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] This modification allows the clock to also be read in 24-hour notation.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] This kind of 12-hour clock can be found in countries where the 24-hour clock is preferred.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Even in those countries where the 12-hour clock is predominant, there are frequently contexts (such as science, medicine, the military or transport) in which the 24-hour clock is preferred.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] In most countries, however, the 24-hour clock is the standard system used, especially in writing.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Some nations in Europe and Latin America use a combination of the two, preferring the 12-hour system in colloquial speech but using the 24-hour system in written form and in formal contexts.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock in speech often uses phrases such as*... in the morning*,*... in the afternoon*,*... in the evening*, and *... at night*.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] *Rider's British Merlin* almanac for 1795 and a similar almanac for 1773 published in London used them.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Other than in English-speaking countries and some Spanish-speaking countries, the terms *a.m.* and *p.m.* are seldom used and often unknown.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] In most countries, computers by default show the time in 24-hour notation.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Most operating systems, including Microsoft Windows and Unix-like systems such as Linux and macOS, activate the 12-hour notation by default for a limited number of language and region settings.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] This behaviour can be changed by the user, such as with the Windows operating system's "Region and Language" settings.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The Latin abbreviations *a.m.* and *p.m.* (often written "am" and "pm", "AM" and "PM", or "A.M." and "P.M.") are used in English (and Spanish).
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] When abbreviations and phrases are omitted, one may rely on sentence context and societal norms to reduce ambiguity.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] For example, if one commutes to work at "9:00", 9:00 a.m. may be implied, but if a social dance is scheduled to begin at "9:00", it may begin at 9:00 p.m.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The terms "a.m." and "p.m." are abbreviations of the Latin *ante meridiem* (before midday) and *post meridiem* (after midday).
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Depending on the style guide referenced, the abbreviations "a.m." and "p.m." are variously written in small capitals ("am" and "pm"), uppercase letters without a period ("AM" and "PM"), uppercase letters with periods, or lowercase letters ("am" and "pm" or "a.m." and "p.m.").
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Some style guides suggest the use of a space between the number and the a.m. or p.m. abbreviation.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Style guides recommend not using a.m. and p.m. without a time preceding it.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The hour/minute separator varies between countries: some use a colon, others use a period (full stop), and still others use the letter h.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] (In some usages, particularly "military time", of the 24-hour clock, there is no separator between hours and minutes.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] In speaking, it is common to round the time to the nearest five minutes and/or express the time as the past (or to) the closest hour; for example, "five past five" (5:05).
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Minutes *past* the hour means those minutes are added to the hour; "ten past five" means 5:10.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Minutes *to, till* and *of* the hour mean those minutes are subtracted; "ten of five", "ten till five", and "ten to five" all mean 4:50.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Fifteen minutes is often called a *quarter hour*, and thirty minutes is often known as a *half hour*.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] For example, 5:15 can be phrased "(a) quarter past five" or "five-fifteen"; 5:30 can be "half past five", "five-thirty" or simply "half five".
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] The time 8:45 may be spoken as "eight forty-five" or "(a) quarter to nine".
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Polish, rounding off is mandatory when using (spoken) 12-hour clock, but disallowed when using 24 hour notation.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] 15:12 might be pronounced as "quarter past three" or "fifteen-twelve", but *not* "three-twelve" or "quarter past fifteen".
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] In older English, it was common for the number 25 to be expressed as "five-and-twenty".
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] In this way the time 8:35 might have been phrased as "five-and-twenty to 9", although this styling fell out of fashion in the later part of the 1900s and is now rarely used.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Instead of meaning 5:30, the "half five" expression is sometimes used to mean 4:30, or "halfway to five", especially for regions such as the American Midwest and other areas that have been particularly influenced by German culture.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] This meaning follows the pattern choices of many Germanic and Slavic languages, including Serbo-Croatian, Dutch, Danish, Russian, Norwegian, and Swedish, as well as Hungarian, Finnish, and the languages of the Baltic States.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Moreover, in situations where the relevant hour is obvious or has been recently mentioned, a speaker might omit the hour and just say "quarter to (the hour)", "half past" or "ten till" to avoid an elaborate sentence in informal conversations.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] These forms are often commonly used in television and radio broadcasts that cover multiple time zones at one-hour intervals.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Minutes may be expressed as an exact number of minutes past the hour specifying the time of day (e.g., 6:32 p.m. is "six thirty-two").
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Additionally, when expressing the time using the "past (after)" or "to (before)" formula, it is conventional to choose the number of minutes below 30 (e.g., 6:32 p.m. is conventionally "twenty-eight minutes to seven" rather than "thirty-two minutes past six").
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] In spoken English, full hours are often represented by the numbered hour followed by *o'clock* (10:00 as *ten o'clock*, 2:00 as *two o'clock*).
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] This may be followed by the "a.m." or "p.m." designator, though some phrases such as *in the morning, in the afternoon, in the evening,* or *at night* more commonly follow analog-style terms such as *o'clock, half past three,* and *quarter to four.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] O'clock* itself may be omitted, telling a time as *four a.m.* or *four p.m.* Minutes ":01" to ":09" are usually pronounced as *oh one* to *oh nine* (*nought* or *zero* can also be used instead of *oh*).
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Minutes ":10" to ":59" are pronounced as their usual number-words.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] For instance, 6:02 a.m. can be pronounced *six oh two a.m.* whereas 6:32 a.m. could be told as *six thirty-two a.m.*.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] It is not always clear what times "12:00 a.m." and "12:00 p.m." denote.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] In Latin, **ante meridiem** (a.m.) means "before midday" and **post meridiem** (p.m.) means "after midday".
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Since noon is neither before nor after itself, the terms a.m. and p.m. do not apply.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Although noon could be denoted "12 m.", this is seldom done and also does not resolve the question of how to indicate midnight.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] By convention, "12 a.m." denotes midnight and "12 p.m." denotes noon.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] However, many style guides recommend against using either because of the potential for confusion.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Many recommend instead using the unambiguous terms "12 noon" and "12 midnight", or simply "noon" and "midnight".
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] These include *The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language*, *The Canadian Press Stylebook*, and the NIST's "Frequently asked questions (FAQ)" web page.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Alternatively, some recommend referring to one minute before or after 12:00, especially when referring to midnight (for example, "11:59 p.m." or "12:01 a.m.").
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] These include the UK's National Physical Laboratory "FAQ-Time" web page.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] That has become common in the United States in legal contracts and for airplane, bus, or train schedules, though some schedules use other conventions.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Occasionally, when trains run at regular intervals, the pattern may be broken at midnight by displacing the midnight departure one or more minutes, such as to 11:59 p.m. or 12:01 a.m.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Some authors have been known to use the reverse of the normal convention.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Richards in his book *Mapping Time* (1999) provided a diagram in which 12 a.m. means noon and 12 p.m. means midnight.
[src:atomic-clock/12-hour-clock] Historically, the style manual of the United States Government Printing Office used 12 a.m. for noon and 12 p.m. for midnight, though this was reversed in its 2008 editions.
[src:atomic-clock/180th-meridian] The **180th meridian** or **antimeridian** is the meridian 180° both east and west of the prime meridian in a geographical coordinate system.
[src:atomic-clock/180th-meridian] The longitude at this line can be given as either east or west.
[src:atomic-clock/180th-meridian] On Earth, the prime and 180th meridians form a great ellipse that divides the planet into the Western and Eastern Hemispheres.
[src:atomic-clock/180th-meridian] The antimeridian passes mostly through the open waters of the Pacific Ocean but also runs across land in Russia, Fiji, and Antarctica.
[src:atomic-clock/180th-meridian] An important function of this meridian is its use as the basis for the International Date Line, which snakes around national borders to maintain date consistency within the territories of Russia, the United States, Kiribati, Fiji and New Zealand.
[src:atomic-clock/180th-meridian] The only places where roads cross this meridian are in Fiji and Russia.
[src:atomic-clock/180th-meridian] Fiji has several such roads and some buildings very close to it.
[src:atomic-clock/180th-meridian] Russia has three roads in the Chukotka Autonomous Okrug.
[src:atomic-clock/180th-meridian] Many geographic software libraries or data formats project the world to a rectangle; very often this rectangle is split exactly at the 180th meridian.
[src:atomic-clock/180th-meridian] This often makes it non-trivial to do simple tasks (like representing an area, or a line) over the 180th meridian.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] In 2019, four of the seven SI base units specified in the International System of Quantities were redefined in terms of natural physical constants, rather than human artefacts such as the standard kilogram.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The second, metre, and candela had previously been redefined using physical constants.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The four new definitions aimed to improve the SI without changing the value of any units, ensuring continuity with existing measurements.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] In November 2018, the 26th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) unanimously approved these changes, which the International Committee for Weights and Measures (CIPM) had proposed earlier that year after determining that previously agreed conditions for the change had been met.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] These conditions were satisfied by a series of experiments that measured the constants to high accuracy relative to the old SI definitions, and were the culmination of decades of research.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The previous major change of the metric system occurred in 1960 when the International System of Units (SI) was formally published.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] At this time the metre was redefined: the definition was changed from the prototype of the metre to a certain number of wavelengths of a spectral line of a krypton-86 radiation, making it derivable from universal natural phenomena.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The kilogram remained defined by a physical prototype, leaving it the only artefact upon which the SI unit definitions depended.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] At this time the SI, as a coherent system, was constructed around seven *base units*, powers of which were used to construct all other units.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] With the 2019 redefinition, the SI is constructed around seven defining *constants*, allowing all units to be constructed directly from these constants.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The designation of base units is retained but is no longer essential to define the SI units.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The metric system was originally conceived as a system of measurement that was derivable from unchanging phenomena, but practical limitations necessitated the use of artefacts – the prototype of the metre and prototype of the kilogram – when the metric system was introduced in France in 1799.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The definitions of some units were defined by measurements that are difficult to precisely realise in a laboratory, such as the kelvin, which was defined in terms of the triple point of water.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] With the 2019 redefinition, the SI became wholly derivable from natural phenomena with most units being based on fundamental physical constants.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] A number of authors have published criticisms of the revised definitions; their criticisms include the premise that the proposal failed to address the impact of breaking the link between the definition of the dalton and the definitions of the kilogram, the mole, and the Avogadro constant.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The basic structure of the SI was developed over about 170 years between 1791 and 1960.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Since 1960, technological advances have made it possible to address weaknesses in the SI such as the dependence on a physical artefact to define the kilogram.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] During the early years of the French Revolution, the leaders of the French National Constituent Assembly decided to introduce a new system of measurement that was based on the principles of logic and natural phenomena.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The metre was defined as one ten-millionth of the distance from the north pole to the equator and the kilogram as the mass of one thousandth of a cubic metre of pure water.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Although these definitions were chosen to avoid ownership of the units, they could not be measured with sufficient convenience or precision to be of practical use.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Instead, realisations were created in the form of the **mètre des Archives** and **kilogramme des Archives**, which were a "best attempt" at fulfilling these principles.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The 1st CGPM (1889) formally approved the use of 40 prototype metres and 40 prototype kilograms made by the British firm Johnson Matthey as the standards mandated by the Convention of the Metre.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] 6 and Kilogram KIII were designated as the international prototype of the metre and the kilogram, respectively; the CGPM retained other copies as working copies, and the rest were distributed to member states for use as their national prototypes.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] About once every 40 years, the national prototypes were compared with and recalibrated against the international prototype.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] In 1921 the Convention of the Metre was revised and the mandate of the CGPM was extended to provide standards for all units of measure, not just mass and length.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] In the ensuing years, the CGPM took on responsibility for providing standards of electrical current (1946), luminosity (1946), temperature (1948), time (1956), and molar mass (1971).
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The 9th CGPM in 1948 instructed the CIPM "to make recommendations for a single practical system of units of measurement, suitable for adoption by all countries adhering to the Metre Convention".
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The recommendations based on this mandate were presented to the 11th CGPM (1960), where they were formally accepted and given the name "**Système International d'Unités**" and its abbreviation "SI".
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The 17th CGPM (1983) replaced the 1960 definition of the metre with one based on the second by giving an exact definition of the speed of light in units of metres per second.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Since their manufacture, drifts of up to 2×10−8 kilograms (20 μg) per year in the national prototype kilograms relative to the international prototype of the kilogram (IPK) have been detected.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] There was no way of determining whether the national prototypes were gaining mass or whether the IPK was losing mass.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Newcastle University metrologist Peter Cumpson has since identified mercury vapour absorption or carbonaceous contamination as possible causes of this drift.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] At the 21st meeting of the CGPM (1999), national laboratories were urged to investigate ways of breaking the link between the kilogram and a specific artefact.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Metrologists investigated several alternative approaches to redefining the kilogram based on fundamental physical constants.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Among others, the Avogadro project and the development of the Kibble balance (known as the "watt balance" before 2016) promised methods of indirectly measuring mass with very high precision.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] These projects provided tools that enable alternative means of redefining the kilogram.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] A report published in 2007 by the Consultative Committee for Thermometry (CCT) to the CIPM noted that their current definition of temperature has proved to be unsatisfactory for temperatures below 20 K and for temperatures above 1300 K.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The committee took the view that the Boltzmann constant provided a better basis for temperature measurement than did the triple point of water because it overcame these difficulties.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] At its 23rd meeting (2007), the CGPM mandated the CIPM to investigate the use of natural constants as the basis for all units of measure rather than the artefacts that were then in use.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The following year this was endorsed by the International Union of Pure and Applied Physics (IUPAP).
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] At a meeting of the CCU held in Reading, United Kingdom, in September 2010, a resolution and draft changes to the SI brochure that were to be presented to the next meeting of the CIPM in October 2010 were agreed to in principle.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The CIPM meeting of October 2010 found "the conditions set by the General Conference at its 23rd meeting have not yet been fully met.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] For this reason the CIPM does not propose a revision of the SI at the present time".
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The CIPM, however, presented a resolution for consideration at the 24th CGPM (17–21 October 2011) to agree to the new definitions in principle, but not to implement them until the details had been finalised.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] This resolution was accepted by the conference, and in addition the CGPM moved the date of the 25th meeting forward from 2015 to 2014.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] At the 25th meeting on 18 to 20 November 2014, it was found that "despite [progress in the necessary requirements] the data do not yet appear to be sufficiently robust for the CGPM to adopt the revised SI at its 25th meeting", thus postponing the revision to the next meeting in 2018.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Measurements accurate enough to meet the conditions were available in 2017 and the redefinition was adopted at the 26th CGPM (13–16 November 2018).
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Following the successful 1983 redefinition of the metre in terms of an exact numerical value for the speed of light, the BIPM's Consultative Committee for Units (CCU) recommended and the BIPM proposed that four further constants of nature should be defined to have exact values.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] As part of the redefinition, the International Prototype of the Kilogram was retired and definitions of the kilogram, the ampere, and the kelvin were replaced.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] These changes have the effect of redefining the SI base units, though the definitions of the SI derived units in terms of the base units remain the same.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Following the CCU proposal, the texts of the definitions of all of the base units were either refined or rewritten, changing the emphasis from explicit-unit-type to explicit-constant-type definitions.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Explicit-unit definitions define a unit in terms of a specific example of that unit; for example, in 1324 Edward II defined the inch as being the length of three barleycorns, and from 1889 to 2019 the kilogram was defined as the mass of the International Prototype of the kilogram.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] In explicit-constant definitions, a constant of nature is given a specified value, and the definition of the unit emerges as a consequence; for example, in 2019, the speed of light was defined as exactly 299792458 metres per second.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The length of the metre could be derived because the second had been already independently defined.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The previous and 2019 definitions are given below.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The new definition of the second is effectively the same as the previous one, the only difference being that the conditions under which the definition applies are more rigorously defined.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The new definition of the metre is effectively the same as the previous one, the only difference being that the additional rigour in the definition of the second propagated to the metre.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The definition of the kilogram fundamentally changed from an artefact (the International Prototype of the Kilogram) to a constant of nature.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Because the Planck constant relates photon energy to photon frequency, the new definition relates the kilogram to the mass equivalent of the energy of a photon at a specific frequency.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The definition of the ampere underwent a major revision.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] For illustration, this is equivalent to defining one coulomb to be an exact specified multiple of the elementary charge.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Because the previous definition contains a reference to force, which has the dimensions MLT−2, it follows that in the previous SI the kilogram, metre, and second – the base units representing these dimensions – had to be defined before the ampere could be defined.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Other consequences of the previous definition were that in SI the value of vacuum permeability (*μ*0) was fixed at exactly 4*π*×10−7 H⋅m−1.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] A consequence of the revised definition is that the ampere no longer depends on the definitions of the kilogram and the metre; it does, however, still depend on the definition of the second.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] In addition, the numerical values when expressed in SI units of the vacuum permeability, vacuum permittivity, and impedance of free space, which were exact before the redefinition, are subject to experimental error after the redefinition.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] For example, the numerical value of the vacuum permeability has a relative uncertainty equal to that of the experimental value of the fine-structure constant $\alpha$ .
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The CODATA 2018 value for the relative standard uncertainty of $\alpha$ is 1.6×10−10.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The definition of the kelvin underwent a fundamental change.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Rather than using the triple point of water to fix the temperature scale, the new definition uses the energy equivalent as given by Boltzmann's equation.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The previous definition of the mole linked it to the kilogram.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The revised definition breaks that link by making a mole a specific number of entities of the substance in question.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] One consequence of this change is that the previously defined relationship between the mass of the 12C atom, the dalton, the kilogram, and the Avogadro constant is no longer exact.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The wording of the 9th SI Brochure implies that the first statement remains valid, which means the second is no longer exactly true.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The molar mass constant, while still with great accuracy remaining 1 g/mol, is no longer exactly equal to that.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The new definition of the candela is effectively the same as the previous definition as dependent on other base units, with the result that the redefinition of the kilogram and the additional rigour in the definitions of the second and metre propagate to the candela.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] All seven of the SI base units are defined in terms of defined constants and universal physical constants.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Seven constants are needed to define the seven base units but there is not a direct correspondence between each specific base unit and a specific constant; except the second and the mole, more than one of the seven constants contributes to the definition of any given base unit.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] When the New SI was first designed, there were more than six suitable physical constants from which the designers could choose.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] For example, once length and time had been established, the universal gravitational constant *G* could, from a dimensional point of view, be used to define mass.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The physical constants were chosen on the basis of minimal uncertainty associated with measuring the constant and the degree of independence of the constant in respect of other constants that were being used.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Much of the work done by the CIPM is delegated to consultative committees.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The CIPM Consultative Committee for Units (CCU) has made the proposed changes while other committees have examined the proposal in detail and have made recommendations regarding their acceptance by the CGPM in 2014.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] As of March 2011, the International Avogadro Coordination (IAC) group had obtained an uncertainty of 3.0×10−8 and NIST had obtained an uncertainty of 3.6×10−8 in their measurements.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] On 1 September 2012 the European Association of National Metrology Institutes (EURAMET) launched a formal project to reduce the relative difference between the Kibble balance and the silicon sphere approach to measuring the kilogram from (17±5)×10−8 to within 2×10−8.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] As of the 2014 CODATA-recommended values of the fundamental physical constants published in 2016 using data collected until the end of 2014, all measurements met the CGPM's requirements, and the redefinition and the next CGPM quadrennial meeting in late 2018 could now proceed.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The vote, which was held on 16 November 2018 at the 26th CGPM, was unanimous; all attending national representatives voted in favour of the revised proposal.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The new definitions became effective on 20 May 2019.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The changes proposed in the new SI only addressed problems with the definition of the base units, including new definitions of the candela and the mole – units Foster argued are not true base units.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Other issues raised by Foster fell outside the scope of the proposal.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Concerns have been expressed that the use of explicit-constant definitions of the unit being defined that are not related to an example of its quantity will have many adverse effects.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] When the scale of the divergence between the IPK and national kilogram prototypes was reported in 2005, a debate began about whether the kilogram should be defined in terms of the mass of the silicon-28 atom or by using the Kibble balance.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] If the mass of a silicon atom were to be determined by the Avogadro project using the Avogadro constant, it could be linked directly to the kilogram.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Concerns that the authors of the proposal had failed to address the impact of breaking the link between the mole, kilogram, dalton, and the Avogadro constant (*N*A) have also been expressed.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] This direct link has caused many to argue that the mole is not a true physical unit but, according to the Swedish philosopher Johansson, a "scaling factor".
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The 8th edition of the SI Brochure defined the dalton in terms of the mass of an atom of 12C.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] It defined the Avogadro constant in terms of this mass and the kilogram, making it determined by experiment.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The redefinition fixes the Avogadro constant and the 9th SI Brochure retains the definition of dalton in terms of 12C, with the effect that the link between the dalton and the kilogram will be broken.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] In 1993, the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) approved the use of the dalton as an alternative name for the unified atomic mass unit with the qualification that the CGPM had not given its approval.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] This would result in the dalton and the atomic mass unit potentially differing from each other with a relative uncertainty of the order of 10−10.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The 9th SI Brochure, however, defines both the dalton (Da) and the unified atomic mass unit (u) as exactly ⁠1/12⁠ of the mass of a free carbon-12 atom and not in relation to the kilogram, with the effect that the above equation will be inexact.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Different temperature ranges need different measurement methods.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Room temperature can be measured by means of expansion and contraction of a liquid in a thermometer but high temperatures are often associated with colour of blackbody radiation.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Chyla, approaching the structure of SI from a philosophical point of view in the *Journal of the Polish Physical Society*, argued that temperature is not a real base unit but is an average of the thermal energies of the individual particles that comprise the body concerned.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Chyla acknowledged, however, that in the macroscopic world, temperature plays the role of a base unit because much of the theory of thermodynamics is based on temperature.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] The Consultative Committee for Thermometry, part of the International Committee for Weights and Measures, publishes a *mise en pratique* (practical technique), last updated in 1990, for measuring temperature.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] At very low and at very high temperatures it often links energy to temperature via the Boltzmann constant.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Foster argued that "luminous intensity [the candela] is not a physical quantity, but a photobiological quantity that exists in human perception", questioning whether the candela should be a base unit.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Before the 1979 decision to define photometric units in terms of luminous flux (power) rather than luminous intensities of standard light sources, there was already doubt whether there should still be a separate base unit for photometry.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] Furthermore, there was unanimous agreement that the lumen was now more fundamental than the candela.
[src:atomic-clock/2019-revision-of-the-si] However, for the sake of continuity the candela was kept as base unit.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Clocks and watches with a **24-hour analog dial** have an hour hand that makes one complete revolution—360°—in a full day, or 24 hours per revolution.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In contrast, the more familiar 12-hour analog dial has an hour hand that completes two revolutions per day, or 12 hours per revolution.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Twenty-four-hour analog clocks and watches are commonly used by logistics workers, firefighters, police officers, paramedics, nurses, pilots, scientists, and military personnel.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] They are often preferred because they present an unambiguous representation of the entire day at once.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] This definition specifically refers to the use of a full circular dial to represent a 24-hour cycle.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Simply using numbers from 0 to 23 (or 1 to 24) is known as the *24-hour clock system*.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Sundials also use 24-hour analog dials, as the shadow follows a path that repeats approximately once per day.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Many sundials are marked with the double-XII (or double-12) system, where the numbers I to XII (or 1 to 12) appear twice—once for the morning and once for the afternoon and evening.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Thus, VI (6) appears twice on many sundial dials: once near sunrise and once near sunset.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Modern 24-hour analog dials—aside from sundials—are almost always marked with 24 numbers or hour markers around the edge, following the 24-hour clock system.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Because they display the entire day in one rotation, they do not require AM or PM indicators.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] The ancient Egyptians divided the day into 24 hours.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] There are diagrams of circles divided into 24 sections in the astronomical ceiling in the tomb of Senemut.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Sundials use some or all of the 24-hour dial, because they show the position of the sun in the sky.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Sometimes, for aesthetic rather than practical reasons, all the 24 hour marks are shown.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Medieval clocks often used the 24-hour analog dial, influenced by the widespread example of the astrolabe.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In Northern Europe, the double-XII system was preferred: two sets of the Roman numerals I to XII were used, one on the left side for the night and morning hours, and another set on the right side of the dial to represent the afternoon and evening hours.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In Italy, the numbers from 1 to 24 (I to XXIV in Roman numerals) were used, leading to the widespread use of the 24-hour system in that country.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] On Italian clocks, though, the I was often shown at the right side of the dial, rather than the top.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] This probably reflects the influence of the Italian timekeeping system, which started counting the hours of the day at sunset or twilight.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In northern Europe, the double-XII system was gradually superseded during the 14th and 15th centuries by the single-XII (12-hour system), leading to the widespread adoption of the 12-hour dial for popular use.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] The 24-hour analog dial continued to be used, but primarily by technicians, astronomers, scientists, and clockmakers.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] John Harrison, Thomas Tompion, and Mudge built a number of clocks with 24-hour analog dials, particularly when building astronomical and nautical instruments.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] 24-hour dials were also used on sidereal clocks.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] The famous Big Ben clock in London has a 24-hour dial as part of the mechanism, although it is not visible from the outside.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Astronauts used the 24-hour format due to the lack of day/night in the space environment.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In the 20th century, the 24-hour analog dial was adopted by radio amateurs, media, pilots, maritime, submariners, government, diplomats and for military use.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] 24-hour analog watches and clocks are still being manufactured today, and are sought after by collectors and enthusiasts.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Manufacturers who make 24-hour analog watches include Glycine, Raketa, Vostok, Fortis, Poljot, Swatch, and many others.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] A few rare variants place noon and midnight at the right and left sides.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] There is no ambiguity if the 24-hour numbering is used.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In the United States, the government and military commonly use 24-hour clocks having noon at the bottom; the variant with noon at the top is far less common.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Multiple time zones can be displayed by having multiple hour hands or a rotating bezel.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] The bezel is a ring around the outside of the watch's face.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] When it is used, the top of the watch always represents midnight (or noon) GMT.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] The bezel, which also has hour markings, is then rotated so that its numbering represents local time.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] So, a pilot always has GMT time available for talking to air traffic control and, when they land, only has to rotate the bezel to "set" the watch to their new local time.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Glycine was the first to feature a 24-hour rotating bezel in 1953 with the Airman No.1 pilot watch.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] The design became widely known when Rolex designed the Rolex GMT Master for Pan-Am pilots in 1954.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] A 24-hour watch with a compass card dial can be used to determine direction when set to local noon and used in conjunction with the Sun.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Many (but not all) digital watches can be set to show the time in 24-hour format.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] A common use for the 24-hour analog method of representing time is for showing the way the time of day depends on one's location.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] George Orwell uses the 12-hour and 24-hour dials to symbolize the old and new worlds in his novel *Nineteen Eighty-Four*.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] The 12-hour dial is a relic of pre-revolutionary society, used to represent the desirable past; the 24-hour dial and time system is the compulsory standard imposed by the Party, and represents both conformity and the undesirable nature of the new world.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] It was a bright cold day in April, and the clocks were striking thirteen.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In the 1927 film *Metropolis*, the opening scene shows both a 24-hour analog clock and a 10-hour (decimal) analog clock, one above the other.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] Both are used to convey the impression of an alien and highly efficient society.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] In Jules Verne's 1870 science fiction masterpiece *Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Seas*, Captain Nemo remarks that the clocks in the *Nautilus* use a 24-hour dial: "Now, look at that clock: it's electric, it runs with an accuracy rivaling the finest chronometers.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] I've had it divided into twenty–four hours like Italian clocks, since neither day nor night, sun nor moon, exist for me, but only this artificial light that I import into the depths of the seas!
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-analogue-dial] A watch with a 24-hour analog dial is important to the resolution of Alfred Bester's 1953 short story "The Roller Coaster".
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] The modern **24-hour clock** is the convention of timekeeping in which the day runs from midnight to midnight and is divided into 24 hours.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] This is indicated by the hours (and minutes) passed since midnight, from 00(:00) to 23(:59), with 24(:00) as an option to indicate the end of the day.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] This system, as opposed to the 12-hour clock, is the most commonly used time notation in the world today, and is used by the international standard ISO 8601.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] A number of countries, particularly English speaking, use the 12-hour clock, or a mixture of the 24- and 12-hour time systems.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] In countries where the 12-hour clock is dominant, some professions prefer to use the 24-hour clock.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] For example, in the practice of medicine, the 24-hour clock is generally used in documentation of care as it prevents any ambiguity as to when events occurred in a patient's medical history.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] To indicate the exact end of the day, hh may take the value 24, with mm and ss taking the value 00.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] In the case of a leap second, the value of ss may extend to 60.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] A leading zero is added for numbers under 10, but it is optional for the hours.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] The leading zero is very commonly used in computer applications, and always used when a specification requires it (for example, ISO 8601).
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] Where subsecond resolution is required, the seconds can be a decimal fraction; that is, the fractional part follows a decimal dot or comma, as in 01:23:45.678.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] The most commonly used separator symbol between hours, minutes and seconds is the colon, which is also the symbol used in ISO 8601.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] In the past, some European countries used the dot on the line as a separator, but most national standards on time notation have since then been changed to the international standard colon.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] In some contexts (including some computer protocols and military time), no separator is used and times are written as, for example, "2359".
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] In the 24-hour time notation, the day begins at midnight, 00:00 or 0:00, and the last minute of the day begins at 23:59.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] In the ISO 8601 notation, 24:00 may also be used to refer to midnight at the end of a given date — that is, 24:00 of one day is the same time as 00:00 of the following day.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] The notation 24:00 mainly serves to refer to the exact end of a day in a time interval.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] A typical usage is giving opening hours ending at midnight (e.g.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] Similarly, some bus and train timetables show 00:00 as departure time and 24:00 as arrival time.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] Legal contracts often run from the start date at 00:00 until the end date at 24:00.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] While the 24-hour notation unambiguously distinguishes between midnight at the start (00:00) and end (24:00) of any given date, there is no commonly accepted distinction among users of the 12-hour notation.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] Style guides and military communication regulations in some English-speaking countries discourage the use of 24:00 even in the 24-hour notation, and recommend reporting times near midnight as 23:59 or 00:01 instead.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] Sometimes the use of 00:00 is also avoided.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] In variance with this, an older version of the correspondence manual for the United States Navy and United States Marine Corps specified 0001 to 2400.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] The manual was updated in June 2015 to use 0000 to 2359.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] Time-of-day notations beyond 24:00 (such as 24:01 or 25:00 instead of 00:01 or 01:00) are not commonly used and not covered by the relevant standards.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] However, they have been used occasionally in some special contexts in the United Kingdom, France, Spain, Canada, Japan, South Korea, Hong Kong, and China where business hours extend beyond midnight, such as broadcast television production and scheduling.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] The GTFS public transport schedule listings file format has the concept of service days and expects times beyond 24:00 for trips that run after midnight.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] For example, Microsoft Windows and macOS activate the 12-hour notation by default only if a computer is in a handful of specific language and region settings.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] The 24-hour system is commonly used in text-based interfaces.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] POSIX programs such as `ls` default to displaying timestamps in 24-hour format.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] In the United States (a country which uses 12-hour clocks), the 24-hour clock is often referred to as *military time*.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] There is, however, a more specific standard for military time which refines the acceptable written and spoken forms of times on the 24-hour clock.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] The first mechanical public clocks introduced in Italy were mechanical 24-hour clocks which counted the 24 hours of the day from one-half hour after sunset to the evening of the following day.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] The 24th hour was the last hour of day time.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] The modern 24-hour system is a late-19th century adaptation of the German midnight-starting system, and then prevailed in the world with the exception of some Anglophone countries.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] Striking clocks had to produce 300 strokes each day, which required a lot of rope, and wore out the mechanism quickly, so some localities switched to ringing sequences of 1 to 12 twice, or 1 to 6 repeated four times.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] Sandford Fleming, the engineer-in-chief of the Canadian Intercolonial Railway, was an early proponent of using the 24-hour clock as part of a programme to reform timekeeping, which also included establishing time zones and a standard prime meridian.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] The Canadian Pacific Railway was among the first organisations to adopt the 24-hour clock, at midsummer 1886.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] A report by a government committee in the United Kingdom noted Italy as the first country among those mentioned to adopt 24-hour time nationally, in 1893.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] Other European countries followed: France adopted it in 1912 (the French army in 1909), followed by Denmark (1916), and Greece (1917).
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] By 1920, Spain, Portugal, Belgium, and Switzerland had switched, followed by Turkey (1925), and Germany (1927).
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] By the early 1920s, many countries in Latin America had also adopted the 24-hour clock.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] Some of the railways in India had switched before the outbreak of the war.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] During World War I, the British Royal Navy adopted the 24-hour clock in 1915, and the Allied armed forces followed soon after, with the British Army switching officially in 1918.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] The Canadian armed forces first started to use the 24-hour clock in late 1917.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] In 1920, the United States Navy was the first United States organisation to adopt the system; the United States Army, however, did not officially adopt the 24-hour clock until 1 July 1942.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] The use of the 24-hour clock in the United Kingdom has grown steadily since the beginning of the 20th century, although attempts to make the system official failed more than once.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] In 1934, the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) switched to the 24-hour clock for broadcast announcements and programme listings.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] The experiment was halted after five months following a lack of enthusiasm from the public, and the BBC continued using the 12-hour clock.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] In the same year, Pan American World Airways Corporation and Western Airlines in the United States both adopted the 24-hour clock.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] In modern times, the BBC uses a mixture of both the 12-hour and the 24-hour clock.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] British Rail, London Transport, and the London Underground switched to the 24-hour clock for timetables in 1964.
[src:atomic-clock/24-hour-clock] A mixture of the 12- and 24-hour clocks similarly prevails in other English-speaking Commonwealth countries: French speakers have adopted the 24-hour clock in Canada much more broadly than English speakers, and Australia as well as New Zealand also use both systems.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] In metaphysics, the **A series** and the **B series** are two different descriptions of the temporal ordering relation among events.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] The two series differ principally in their use of tense to describe the temporal relation between events and the resulting ontological implications regarding time.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] John McTaggart introduced these terms in 1908, in an argument for the unreality of time.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] They are now commonly used by contemporary philosophers of time.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] Metaphysical debate about temporal orderings reaches back to the ancient Greek philosophers Heraclitus and Parmenides.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] Parmenides thought that reality is timeless and unchanging.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] Heraclitus, in contrast, believed that the world is a process of ceaseless change, flux and decay.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] Reality for Heraclitus is dynamic and ephemeral, in a state of constant flux, as in his famous statement that it is impossible to step twice into the same river (since the river is flowing).
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] McTaggart distinguished the ancient conceptions as a set of relations.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] According to McTaggart, there are two distinct modes in which all events can be ordered in time.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] In the first mode (the A series of temporal positions), events are ordered as future, present, and past.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] Futurity and pastness allow for degrees, while the present does not.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] When we speak of time in this way, we are speaking in terms of a series of positions which run from the remote past through the recent past to the present, and from the present through the near future all the way to the remote future.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] The essential characteristic of this descriptive modality is **McTaggartian change**: the continual transformation of an event's position within the series of temporal positions, whereby the event is first future, then present, and then past.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] In this sense, change is understood as temporal passage itself, through which events acquire and lose the determinations of futurity, presentness, and pastness.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] Moreover, assertions made according to this modality correspond to the temporal perspective of the person who utters them.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] This is the A series of temporal positions.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] Although originally McTaggart defined tenses as relational qualities, i.e., qualities that events possess by standing in a certain relation to something outside of time (that does not change its position in time), today it is popularly believed that he treated tenses as monadic properties.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] Later philosophers have independently inferred that McTaggart must have understood tense as monadic because English tenses are normally expressed by the non-relational singular predicates "is past", "is present" and "is future", as noted by R.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] An important difference between the two series is that while events continuously change their position in the A series, their position in the B series does not.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] If an event is ever earlier than some events and later than the rest, it is always earlier than and later than those very events.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] Furthermore, while events acquire their A-series determinations through a relation to something outside of time, their B-series determinations hold between the events that constitute the B series.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] This is the B series, and the philosophy that says all truths about time can be reduced to B series statements is the B-theory of time.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] The logic and the linguistic expression of the two series are radically different.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] The A series is *tensed* and the B series is *tenseless*.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] For example, the assertion "it is raining here today" is a tensed assertion because it depends on the temporal perspective—the present—of the person who utters it, while the assertion "It rained here on 29 June 2026" is tenseless because it does not so depend.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] From the point of view of their truth-values, the two propositions are identical (both true or both false) if the first assertion is made on 29 June 2026.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] The non-temporal relation of precedence between two events, say "E precedes F", does not change over time (excluding from this discussion the issue of the relativity of temporal order of causally disconnected events in the theory of relativity).
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] On the other hand, the character of being "past, present or future" of the events "E" or "F" does change with time.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] In the image of McTaggart the passage of time consists in the fact that terms ever further in the future pass into the present...or that the present advances toward terms ever farther in the future.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] If we assume the first point of view, we speak as if the B series slides along a fixed A series.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] If we assume the second point of view, we speak as if the A series slides along a fixed B series.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] There are two principal varieties of the A-theory, presentism and the growing block universe.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] Both assume an objective present, but presentism assumes that only present objects exist, while the growing block universe assumes both present and past objects exist, but not future ones.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] Views that assume no objective present and are therefore versions of the B-theory include eternalism and four-dimensionalism.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] Vincent Conitzer argues that A-theory is related to Benj Hellie's vertiginous question and Caspar Hare's ideas of egocentric presentism and perspectival realism.
[src:atomic-clock/a-series-and-b-series] He argues that A-theory being true and "now" being metaphysically distinguished from other moments of time implies that the "I" is also metaphysically distinguished from other first-person perspectives.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] A version of the concept of absolute space (in the sense of a preferred frame) can be seen in Aristotelian physics.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] Westman writes that a "whiff" of absolute space can be observed in Copernicus's *De revolutionibus orbium coelestium*, where Copernicus uses the concept of an immobile sphere of stars.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] Originally introduced by Sir Isaac Newton in *Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica*, the concepts of absolute time and space provided a theoretical foundation that facilitated Newtonian mechanics.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] According to Newton, absolute time exists independently of any perceiver and progresses at a consistent pace throughout the universe.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] Unlike relative time, Newton believed absolute time was imperceptible and could only be understood mathematically.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] According to Newton, humans are only capable of perceiving relative time, which is a measurement of perceivable objects in motion (like the Moon or Sun).
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] From these movements, we infer the passage of time.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] These notions imply that absolute space and time do not depend upon physical events, but are a backdrop or stage setting within which physical phenomena occur.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] Thus, every object has an absolute state of motion relative to absolute space, so that an object must be either in a state of absolute rest, or moving at some absolute speed.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] Historically, there have been differing views on the concept of absolute space and time.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] Gottfried Leibniz was of the opinion that space made no sense except as the relative location of bodies, and time made no sense except as the relative movement of bodies.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] A more recent form of these objections was made by Ernst Mach.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] Mach's principle proposes that mechanics is entirely about relative motion of bodies and, in particular, mass is an expression of such relative motion.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] So, for example, a single particle in a universe with no other bodies would have zero mass.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] According to Mach, Newton's examples simply illustrate relative rotation of spheres and the bulk of the universe.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] These views opposing absolute space and time may be seen from a modern stance as an attempt to introduce operational definitions for space and time, a perspective made explicit in the special theory of relativity.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] Even within the context of Newtonian mechanics, the modern view is that absolute space is unnecessary.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] Instead, the notion of inertial frame of reference has taken precedence, that is, a preferred *set* of frames of reference that move uniformly with respect to one another.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] Newton himself recognized the role of inertial frames.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] As a practical matter, inertial frames often are taken as frames moving uniformly with respect to the fixed stars.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] See Inertial frame of reference for more discussion on this.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] I do not define time, space, place and motion, as being well known to all.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] The concepts of space and time were separate in physical theory prior to the advent of special relativity theory, which connected the two and showed both to be dependent upon the reference frame's motion.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] In Einstein's theories, the ideas of absolute time and space were superseded by the notion of spacetime in special relativity, and curved spacetime in general relativity.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] Quoted below from his later papers, Einstein identified the term aether with "properties of space", a terminology that is not widely used.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] Einstein stated that in general relativity the "aether" is not absolute anymore, as the geodesic and therefore the structure of spacetime depends on the presence of matter.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] Special relativity eliminates absolute time (although Gödel and others suspect absolute time may be valid for some forms of general relativity) and general relativity further reduces the physical scope of absolute space and time through the concept of geodesics.
[src:atomic-clock/absolute-space-and-time] There appears to be absolute space in relation to the distant stars because the local geodesics eventually channel information from these stars, but it is not necessary to invoke absolute space with respect to any system's physics, as its local geodesics are sufficient to describe its spacetime.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] An **atomic clock** is a clock that measures time by monitoring the resonant frequency of atoms.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] It is based on the fact that atoms have quantised energy levels, and transitions between such levels are driven by very specific frequencies of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This definition underpins the system of TAI, which is maintained by an ensemble of atomic clocks around the world.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The system of UTC — the basis of civil time — implements leap seconds to allow clock time to stay within one second of Earth's rotation.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The accurate time-keeping capabilities of atomic clocks are also used for navigation by satellite networks such as the EU’s Galileo Programme and the United States’ GPS.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The timing accuracy of the atomic clocks matters because even a timing error of 1 nanosecond (10−9 s) corresponds to a positional error of roughly 30 cm when multiplied by the speed of light.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The main variety of atomic clock in use today employs caesium atoms (or ions) cooled to near absolute zero.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] For example, the United States’ primary standard, the NIST caesium fountain clock named NIST-F2, operates with a relative uncertainty around 10−16.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In July 2025, researchers at the National Institute of Standards and Technology in the United States reported a record-setting optical atomic clock based on a trapped aluminium ion.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This "quantum logic" clock achieves a systematic uncertainty corresponding to around 19 decimal places of accuracy, representing a 41% improvement over the previous record and being 2.6 times more stable than any other ion clock.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The rapid improvement in optical atomic clock performance has prompted the global time-and-frequency community to prepare for a possible redefinition of the SI second.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In June 2025, a coordinated international comparison of optical clocks across six countries was reported — marking a major step towards establishing a global optical-time standard.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Optical atomic clocks are enabling new applications: ultra-precise time- and-frequency dissemination, improved global navigation satellite systems, relativistic geodesy (measuring differences in gravitational potential via clock rates), and tests of fundamental constants and general relativity.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] During the 1930s, the American physicist Isidor Isaac Rabi built equipment for atomic beam magnetic resonance frequency clocks.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The accuracy of mechanical, electromechanical and quartz clocks is reduced by temperature fluctuations.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This led to the idea of measuring the frequency of an atom's vibrations to keep time more accurately, as proposed by James Clerk Maxwell, Lord Kelvin, and Isidor Rabi.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] A prototype measuring phase transitions of the ammonia molecule was developed in 1949.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The first practical atomic clock using caesium atoms was built at the National Physical Laboratory in the United Kingdom in 1955 by Louis Essen in collaboration with Jack Parry.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In 1949, Alfred Kastler and Jean Brossel developed a technique called optical pumping for electron energy level transitions in atoms using light.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This technique is useful for creating much stronger magnetic resonance and microwave absorption signals.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Unfortunately, this caused a side effect with a light shift of the resonant frequency.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Claude Cohen-Tannoudji and others managed to reduce the light shifts to acceptable levels.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Ramsey developed a method, now commonly known as Ramsey interferometry, for higher frequencies and narrower resonances in the oscillating fields.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Kolsky, Phipps, Ramsey, and Silsbee used this technique for molecular beam spectroscopy in 1950.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] During the 1950s, the National Radio Company sold more than 50 units of the first atomic clock, the Atomichron.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In 1964, engineers at Hewlett-Packard released the 5060 rack-mounted model of caesium clocks.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In 1968, the SI defined the duration of the second to be 9192631770 vibrations of the unperturbed ground-state hyperfine transition frequency of the caesium-133 atom.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Prior to that it was defined by there being 31556925.9747 seconds in the tropical year 1900.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In 1997, the International Committee for Weights and Measures (CIPM) added that the preceding definition refers to a caesium atom at rest at a temperature of absolute zero.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Following the 2019 revision of the SI, the definition of every base unit except the mole and almost every derived unit relies on the definition of the second.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Timekeeping researchers seek an even more stable atomic reference for the second, with a plan to find a more precise definition of the second as atomic clocks improve based on optical clocks or the Rydberg constant around 2030.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Technological developments such as lasers and optical frequency combs in the 1990s led to increasing accuracy of atomic clocks.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Lasers enable the possibility of optical-range control over atomic states transitions, which has a much higher frequency than that of microwaves; while optical frequency comb measures highly accurately such high frequency oscillation in light.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The first advance beyond the precision of caesium clocks occurred at NIST in 2010 with the demonstration of a "quantum logic" optical clock that used aluminum ions to achieve a precision of 10−17.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Optical clocks are a very active area of research in the field of metrology as scientists work to develop clocks based on elements ytterbium, mercury, aluminum, and strontium.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Scientists at JILA demonstrated a strontium clock with a frequency precision of 10−18 in 2015.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Scientists at NIST developed a quantum logic clock that measured a single aluminum ion in 2019 with a frequency uncertainty of 9.4×10−19.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] At JILA in September 2021, scientists demonstrated an optical strontium clock with a differential frequency precision of 7.6×10−21 between atomic ensembles separated by 1 mm.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The second is expected to be redefined when the field of optical clocks matures, sometime around the year 2030 or 2034.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In order for this to occur, optical clocks must be consistently capable of measuring frequency with accuracy at or better than 2×10−18.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In addition, methods for reliably comparing different optical clocks around the world in national metrology labs must be demonstrated, and the comparison must show relative clock frequency accuracies at or better than 5×10−18.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Reducing the size and power consumption of optical clocks is necessary to enable their use in geodesy and GPS navigation.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In August 2004, NIST scientists demonstrated a chip-scale atomic clock that was 100 times smaller than an ordinary atomic clock and had a much smaller power consumption of 125 mW.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The atomic clock was about the size of a grain of rice with a frequency of about 9 GHz.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This technology became available commercially in 2011.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] An atomic clock is based on a system of atoms which may be in one of two possible energy states.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] A group of atoms is prepared in a lower energy state, and then subjected to microwave radiation.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] If the radiation is of the correct frequency, a number of atoms will transition to the higher energy state.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The closer the frequency is to the inherent oscillation frequency of the atoms, the more atoms will switch states.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Such correlation allows very accurate tuning of the frequency of the microwave radiation.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Once the microwave radiation is adjusted to a known frequency where the maximum number of atoms switch states, the atom and thus, its associated transition frequency, can be used as a timekeeping oscillator to measure elapsed time.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] All timekeeping devices use oscillatory phenomena to accurately measure time, whether it is the rotation of the Earth for a sundial, the swinging of a pendulum in a grandfather clock, the vibrations of springs and gears in a watch, or voltage changes in a quartz crystal watch.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] However all of these are easily affected by temperature changes and are not very accurate.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The most accurate clocks use atomic vibrations to keep track of time.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Clock transition states in atoms are insensitive to temperature and other environmental factors and the oscillation frequency is much higher than any of the other clocks (in microwave frequency regime and higher).
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] One of the most important factors in a clock's performance is the atomic line quality factor, *Q*, which is defined as the ratio of the absolute frequency $\nu _{0}$ of the resonance to the linewidth of the resonance itself $\Delta \nu$ .
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Atomic resonance has a much higher *Q* than mechanical devices.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks can also be isolated from environmental effects to a much higher degree.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks have the benefit that atoms are universal, which means that the oscillation frequency is also universal.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This is different from quartz and mechanical time measurement devices that do not have a universal frequency.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] A clock's quality can be specified by two parameters: accuracy and stability.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Accuracy is a measurement of the degree to which the clock's ticking rate can be counted on to match some absolute standard such as the inherent hyperfine frequency of an isolated atom or ion.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Stability describes how the clock performs when averaged over time to reduce the impact of noise and other short-term fluctuations (see precision).
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The instability of an atomic clock is specified by its Allan deviation $\sigma _{y}(\tau )$ .
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] where $\Delta \nu$ is the spectroscopic linewidth of the clock system, N is the number of atoms or ions used in a single measurement, $T_{\text{c}}$ is the time required for one cycle, and $\tau$ is the averaging period.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This means instability is smaller when the linewidth $\Delta \nu$ is smaller and when ${\sqrt {N}}$ (the signal to noise ratio) is larger.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The stability improves as the time $\tau$ over which the measurements are averaged increases from seconds to hours to days.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The stability is most heavily affected by the oscillator frequency $\nu _{0}$ .
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This is why optical clocks such as strontium clocks (429 terahertz) are much more stable than caesium clocks (9.19 GHz).
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Modern clocks such as atomic fountains or optical lattices that use sequential interrogation are found to generate a type of noise that mimics and adds to the instability inherent in atom or ion counting.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This effect is called the Dick effect and is typically the primary stability limitation for the newer atomic clocks.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] It is an aliasing effect; high frequency noise components in the local oscillator ("LO") are heterodyned to near zero frequency by harmonics of the repeating variation in feedback sensitivity to the LO frequency.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The effect places new and stringent requirements on the LO, which must now have low phase noise in addition to high stability, thereby increasing the cost and complexity of the system.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This expression shows the same dependence on $T_{c}/{\tau }$ as does $\sigma _{y,\,{\rm {atoms}}}(\tau )$ , and, for many of the newer clocks, is significantly larger.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Analysis of the effect and its consequence as applied to optical standards has been treated in a major review (Ludlow, et al., 2015) that lamented on "the pernicious influence of the Dick effect", and in several other papers.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The core of atomic clocks contain a microwave cavity containing a gas.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In a hydrogen maser clock, the gas emits microwaves (*masering*) on a hyperfine transition.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] As the field in the cavity oscillates, the cavity is tuned for maximum microwave amplitude.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The adjustment tries to correct for unwanted side-effects, such as frequencies from other electron transitions, temperature changes, and the spreading in frequencies caused by the vibration of molecules, including Doppler broadening.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Many of the newer clocks, including microwave clocks such as trapped-ion or fountain clocks, and optical clocks such as lattice clocks, use a sequential interrogation protocol rather than the frequency-modulation interrogation.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] An advantage of sequential interrogation is that it can accommodate much higher Qs, with ringing times of seconds rather than milliseconds.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] These clocks also typically have a *dead time*, during which the atom or ion collections are analyzed, renewed and driven into a proper quantum state, after which they are interrogated with a signal from a *local oscillator* (LO) for a time of perhaps a second or so.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Analysis of the final state of the atoms is then used to generate a correction signal to keep the LO frequency locked to that of the atoms or ions.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The accuracy of atomic clocks has improved continuously since the first prototype in the 1950s.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The first generation of atomic clocks were based on measuring caesium, rubidium, and hydrogen atoms.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In a time period from 1959 to 1998, NIST developed a series of seven caesium-133 microwave clocks named NBS-1 to NBS-6 and NIST-7 after the agency changed its name from the National Bureau of Standards to the National Institute of Standards and Technology.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The first clock had an accuracy of 10−11, and the last clock had an accuracy of 10−15.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The clocks were the first to use a caesium fountain, which was introduced by Jerrod Zacharias, and laser cooling of atoms, which was demonstrated by Dave Wineland and his colleagues in 1978.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The next step in atomic clock advances involves going from accuracies of 10−15 to accuracies of 10−18 and even 10−19.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The goal is to redefine the second when clocks become so accurate that they will not lose or gain more than a second in the age of the universe.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] To do so, scientists must demonstrate the accuracy of clocks that use strontium and ytterbium and optical lattice technology.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Such clocks are also called optical clocks where the energy level transitions used are in the optical regime (giving rise to even higher oscillation frequency), which thus, have much higher accuracy as compared to traditional atomic clocks.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The goal of an atomic clock with 10−16 accuracy was first reached at the United Kingdom's National Physical Laboratory's NPL-CsF2 caesium fountain clock and the United States' NIST-F2.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The increase in precision from NIST-F1 to NIST-F2 is due to liquid nitrogen cooling of the microwave interaction region; the largest source of uncertainty in NIST-F1 is the effect of black-body radiation from the warm chamber walls.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The performance of primary and secondary frequency standards contributing to International Atomic Time (TAI) is evaluated.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The evaluation reports of individual (mainly primary) clocks are published online by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures (BIPM).
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] They do this by designing and building frequency standards that produce electric oscillations at a frequency whose relationship to the transition frequency of caesium 133 is known, in order to achieve a very low uncertainty.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] These primary frequency standards estimate and correct various frequency shifts, including relativistic Doppler shifts linked to atomic motion, the thermal radiation of the environment (blackbody shift) and several other factors.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The best primary standards currently produce the SI second with an accuracy approaching an uncertainty of one part in 1016.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] At this level of accuracy, the differences in the gravitational field in the device cannot be ignored.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The standard is then considered in the framework of general relativity to provide a proper time at a specific point.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Atomic time standards such as International Atomic Time (TAI) and Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) are disseminated to the public through satellite navigation systems, radio time signals, and network-based time services.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] These tools can be used to observe clock deviation and synchronization discrepancies in end-user devices.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The International Bureau of Weights and Measures (BIPM) provides a list of frequencies that serve as secondary representations of the second.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This list contains the frequency values and respective standard uncertainties for the rubidium microwave transition and other optical transitions, including neutral atoms and single trapped ions.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] These secondary frequency standards can be as accurate as one part in 1018; however, the uncertainties in the list are one part in 1014–1016.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This is because the uncertainty in the central caesium standard against which the secondary standards are calibrated is one part in 1014–1016.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Primary frequency standards can be used to calibrate the frequency of other clocks used in national laboratories.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] These are usually commercial caesium clocks having very good long-term frequency stability, maintaining a frequency with a stability better than 1 part in 1014 over a few months.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The uncertainty of the primary standard frequencies is around one part in 1013.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Hydrogen masers, which rely on the 1.4 GHz hyperfine transition in atomic hydrogen, are also used in time metrology laboratories.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Masers outperform any commercial caesium clock in terms of short-term frequency stability.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In the past, these instruments have been used in all applications that require a steady reference across time periods of less than one day (frequency stability of about 1 part in ten for averaging times of a few hours).
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Because some active hydrogen masers have a modest but predictable frequency drift with time, they have become an important part of the BIPM's ensemble of commercial clocks that implement International Atomic Time.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The time readings of clocks operated in metrology labs operating with the BIPM need to be known very accurately.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Some operations require synchronization of atomic clocks separated by great distances over thousands of kilometers.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Global Navigational Satellite Systems (GNSS) provide a satisfactory solution to the problem of time transfer.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks are used to broadcast time signals in the United States Global Positioning System (GPS), the Russian Federation's Global Navigation Satellite System (GLONASS), the European Union's Galileo system and China's BeiDou system.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The signal received from one satellite in a metrology laboratory equipped with a receiver with an accurately known position allows the time difference between the local time scale and the GNSS system time to be determined with an uncertainty of a few nanoseconds when averaged over 15 minutes.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Receivers allow the simultaneous reception of signals from several satellites, and make use of signals transmitted on two frequencies.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] As more satellites are launched and start operations, time measurements will become more accurate.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] These methods of time comparison must make corrections for the effects of special relativity and general relativity of a few nanoseconds.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] These four European labs are developing and host a variety of experimental optical clocks that harness different elements in different experimental set-ups and want to compare their optical clocks against each other and check whether they agree.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] National laboratories usually operate a range of clocks.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] These are operated independently of one another and their measurements are sometimes combined to generate a scale that is more stable and more accurate than that of any individual contributing clock.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This scale allows for time comparisons between different clocks in the laboratory.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] These atomic time scales are generally referred to as TA(k) for laboratory k.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) is the result of comparing clocks in national laboratories around the world to International Atomic Time (TAI), then adding leap seconds as necessary.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] TAI is a weighted average of around 450 clocks in some 80 time institutions.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The relative stability of TAI is around one part in 1016.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Before TAI is published, the frequency of the result is compared with the SI second at various primary and secondary frequency standards.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This requires relativistic corrections to be applied to the location of the primary standard which depend on the distance between the equal gravity potential and the rotating geoid of Earth.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The values of the rotating geoid and the TAI change slightly each month and are available in the BIPM Circular T publication.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The TAI time-scale is deferred by a few weeks as the average of atomic clocks around the world is calculated.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] TAI is not distributed in everyday timekeeping.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Instead, an integer number of leap seconds are added or subtracted to correct for the Earth's rotation, producing UTC.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The number of leap seconds is changed so that mean solar noon at the prime meridian (Greenwich) does not deviate from UTC noon by more than 0.9 seconds.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] National metrology institutions maintain an approximation of UTC referred to as UTC(k) for laboratory k.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] UTC(k) is distributed by the BIPM's Consultative Committee for Time and Frequency.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The offset UTC-UTC(k) is calculated every 5 days, the results are published monthly.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks record UTC(k) to no more than 100 nanoseconds.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In some countries, UTC(k) is the legal time that is distributed by radio, television, telephone, Internet, fiber-optic cables, time signal transmitters, and speaking clocks.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In addition, GNSS provides time information accurate to a few tens of nanoseconds or better.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In a next phase, these labs strive to transmit comparison signals in the visible spectrum through fibre-optic cables.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This will allow their experimental optical clocks to be compared with an accuracy similar to the expected accuracies of the optical clocks themselves.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Some of these labs have already established fibre-optic links, and tests have begun on sections between Paris and Teddington, and Paris and Braunschweig.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Fibre-optic links between experimental optical clocks also exist between the American NIST lab and its partner lab JILA, both in Boulder, Colorado but these span much shorter distances than the European network and are between just two labs.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] According to Fritz Riehle, a physicist at PTB, "Europe is in a unique position as it has a high density of the best clocks in the world".
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The fractional uncertainty of the whole link was assessed to be 2.5×10−19, making comparisons of even more accurate clocks possible.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In 2021, NIST compared transmission of signals from a series of experimental atomic clocks located about 1.5 km (1 mi) apart at the NIST lab, its partner lab JILA, and the University of Colorado all in Boulder, Colorado over air and fiber optic cable to a precision of 8×10−18.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The SI second is defined as a certain number of unperturbed ground-state hyperfine transitions of the caesium-133 atom.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Caesium standards are therefore regarded as primary time and frequency standards.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Caesium clocks include the NIST-F1 clock, developed in 1999, and the NIST-F2 clock, developed in 2013.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Caesium has several properties that make it a good choice for an atomic clock.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Whereas a hydrogen atom moves at 1,600 m/s at room temperature and a nitrogen atom moves at 510 m/s, a caesium atom moves at a much slower speed of 130 m/s due to its greater mass.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The hyperfine frequency of caesium (~9.19 GHz) is also higher than other elements such as rubidium (~6.8 GHz) and hydrogen (~1.4 GHz).
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The high frequency of caesium allows for more accurate measurements.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Caesium reference tubes suitable for national standards currently last about seven years and cost about US$35,000.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Primary frequency and time standards like the United States Time Standard atomic clocks, NIST-F1 and NIST-F2, use far higher power.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In a caesium beam frequency reference, timing signals are derived from a high stability voltage-controlled quartz crystal oscillator (VCXO) that is tunable over a narrow range.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The output frequency of the VCXO (typically 5 MHz) is multiplied by a frequency synthesizer to obtain microwaves at the frequency of the caesium atomic hyperfine transition (about 9192.6317 MHz).
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The output of the frequency synthesizer is amplified and applied to a chamber containing caesium gas which absorbs the microwaves.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The output current of the caesium chamber increases as absorption increases.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The remainder of the circuitry simply adjusts the running frequency of the VCXO to maximize the output current of the caesium chamber which keeps the oscillator tuned to the resonance frequency of the hyperfine transition.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The BIPM defines the unperturbed ground-state hyperfine transition frequency of the rubidium-87 atom; 6,834,682,610.9043126 Hz; in terms of the caesium standard frequency.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks based on rubidium standards are therefore regarded as secondary representations of the second.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The advantages of rubidium atomic clocks are their low cost, small size (commercial standards are as small as 1.7×105 mm3) and short-term stability.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] They are used in many commercial, portable and aerospace applications.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Modern rubidium standard tubes last more than ten years, and can cost as little as US$50.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Some commercial applications use a rubidium standard periodically corrected by a global positioning system receiver (see GPS disciplined oscillator).
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This achieves excellent short-term accuracy, with long-term accuracy equal to (and traceable to) the US national time standards.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The BIPM defines the unperturbed optical transition frequency of the hydrogen-1 neutral atom; 1,233,030,706,593,514 Hz; in terms of the caesium standard frequency.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks based on hydrogen standards are therefore regarded as secondary representations of the second.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Hydrogen masers have superior short-term stability compared to other standards, but lower long-term accuracy.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The long-term stability of hydrogen maser standards decreases because of changes in the cavity's properties over time.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The relative error of hydrogen masers is 5 × 10−16 for periods of 1000 seconds.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This makes hydrogen masers good for radio astronomy, in particular for very long baseline interferometry.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Hydrogen masers are used for flywheel oscillators in laser-cooled atomic frequency standards and broadcasting time signals from national standards laboratories, although they need to be corrected as they drift from the correct frequency over time.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The hydrogen maser is also useful for experimental tests of the effects of special relativity and general relativity such as gravitational red shift.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Optical clocks operate similarly to microwave clocks, but at much higher frequencies, around 1015 Hz rather than the 1010 Hz range of microwave clocks.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The advantage of optical clocks can be explained by the statement that the instability $\sigma \propto {\frac {\Delta f}{f}}{\frac {1}{S/N}}$ , where $\sigma$ is the instability, *f* is the frequency, and *S*/*N* is the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Optical clocks are based on forbidden optical transitions in ions or atoms, with a natural linewidth $\Delta f$ of typically 1 Hz, so the Q-factor is about 1015.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Compared to microwave clocks, the 105 times higher frequency gives better stability, which means that they can facilitate evaluation of lower uncertainties.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] They faster "tick" also gives better time resolution for short intervals.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Optical clocks were enabled by the development of the frequency comb, which allowed cycle-exact counting of these extremely high optical frequencies.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Optical clocks use either a single ion, or an optical lattice with 104–106 atoms.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] A further variation on the optical atomic clock being developed the use of a *nuclear* energy transition (between different nuclear isomers) rather than the atomic electron transitions which current atomic clocks measure.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Most nuclear transitions operate at far too high a frequency to be measured, but the exceptionally low excitation energy of 229m Th produces "gamma rays" in the ultraviolet frequency range.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In 2003, Ekkehard Peik and Christian Tamm noted this makes a clock possible with current optical frequency-measurement techniques.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In 2012, it was shown that a nuclear clock based on a single 229 Th3+ ion could provide a total fractional frequency inaccuracy of 1.5×10−19, which was better than existing 2019 optical atomic clock technology.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Although neutral 229m Th atoms decay in microseconds by internal conversion, this pathway is energetically prohibited in 229m Th+ ions, as the second and higher ionization energy is greater than the nuclear excitation energy, giving 229m Th+ ions a long half-life on the order of 103 s.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] It is the large ratio between transition frequency and isomer lifetime which gives the clock a high quality factor.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The extremely high quality factor also makes the transition frequency very difficult to find, and the 2010s were spent searching for it.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] A sufficiently precise measurement was finally achieved in 2024 as 2,020,407,384,335±2 kHz.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The first experimental optical nuclear clocks were announced in June 2026.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] They are not yet competitive with other atomic clocks, but development is expected to be rapid.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Due to its small size and the shielding effect of the surrounding electrons, an atomic nucleus is much less sensitive to ambient electromagnetic fields than is an electron in an orbital.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Because of the aforementioned insensitivity to ambient fields, it is not necessary to have the clock atoms well-separated in a dilute gas.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Current measurements take advantage of the Mössbauer effect and place the thorium ions in a solid, which allows billions of atoms to be interrogated.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In 2022, the best realisation of the second is done with caesium fountain primary standard clocks such as IT-CsF2, NIST-F2, NPL-CsF2, PTB-CSF2, SU–CsFO2 or SYRTE-FO2.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] These clocks work by laser-cooling a cloud of caesium atoms to a microkelvin in a magneto-optic trap.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] These cold atoms are then launched vertically by laser light.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The atoms then undergo Ramsey excitation in a microwave cavity.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The fraction of excited atoms are then detected by laser beams.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] These clocks have 5×10−16 systematic uncertainty, which is equivalent to 50 picoseconds per day.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] A system of several fountains worldwide contributes to International Atomic Time.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] These caesium clocks also underpin optical frequency measurements.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The development of optical alomic clocks more stable than the best caesium clocks has led to proposals for redefining the second more accurately.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] However, there are several optical clock systems in active development, and it is not clear which is the best to serve as a long-term replacement for the caesium standard.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] An alternative would be to define the second by fixing the Rydberg constant to a certain value: $R_{\infty }={\frac {m_{e}e^{4}}{8\varepsilon _{0}^{2}h^{3}c}}={\frac {m_{e}c\alpha ^{2}}{2h}}$ .
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The Rydberg constant describes the energy levels in a hydrogen atom with the nonrelativistic approximation $E_{n}\approx -{\frac {R_{\infty }ch}{n^{2}}}$ .
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The only viable way to fix the Rydberg constant involves trapping and cooling hydrogen atoms.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Unfortunately, this is difficult because they are very light and move very fast, causing Doppler shifts.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The radiation needed to cool the hydrogen —121.5 nm— is also difficult to work with.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Another hurdle involves improving the uncertainty in quantum electrodynamics/QED calculations.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In the Report of the 25th meeting of the Consultative Committee for Units (2021), 3 options were considered for the redefinition of the second sometime around 2026, 2030, or 2034.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The first redefinition approach considered was a definition based on a single atomic reference transition.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The second redefinition approach considered was a definition based on a collection of frequencies.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The third redefinition approach considered was a definition based on fixing the numerical value of a fundamental constant, such as making the Rydberg constant the basis for the definition.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The committee concluded there was no feasible way to redefine the second with the third option, since no physical constant is known to enough digits currently to enable realizing the second with a constant.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] A redefinition must include improved optical clock reliability.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] TAI must be contributed to by optical clocks before the BIPM affirms a redefinition.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] A consistent method of communicating the resultant signals, such as fibre optics, must be developed before the second is redefined.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Representations of the second other than the SI cesium standard are motivated by the increasing accuracy of other atomic clocks.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In particular the high frequencies and small linewidths of optical clocks promise significantly improved signal-to-noise ratio and instability.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Further secondary representations would aid in the preparation of a future redefinition of the second.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] A list of frequencies recommended for secondary representations of the second is maintained by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures (BIPM) since 2006 and is available online.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The list contains the frequency values and the respective standard uncertainties for the rubidium microwave transition and for several optical transitions.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] These secondary frequency standards are accurate at the level of 10−18; however, the uncertainties provided in the list are in the range 10−14 – 10−15 since they are limited by the linking to the caesium primary standard that currently (2018) defines the second.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Twenty-first century experimental atomic clocks that provide non-caesium-based secondary representations of the second are becoming so precise that they are likely to be used as extremely sensitive detectors for other things besides measuring frequency and time.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] For example, the frequency of atomic clocks is altered slightly by gravity, magnetic fields, electrical fields, force, motion, temperature and other phenomena.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The experimental clocks tend to continue to improve, and leadership in performance has shifted back and forth between various types of experimental clocks.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The development of atomic clocks has led to many scientific and technological advances such as precise global and regional navigation satellite systems, and applications in the Internet, which depend critically on frequency and time standards.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks are installed at sites of time signal radio transmitters.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] They are used at some long-wave and medium-wave broadcasting stations to deliver a very precise carrier frequency.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks are used in many scientific disciplines, such as for long-baseline interferometry in radio astronomy.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The Global Positioning System (GPS) operated by the United States Space Force provides very accurate timing and frequency signals.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] A GPS receiver works by measuring the relative time delay of signals from a minimum of four, but usually more, GPS satellites, each of which has at least two onboard caesium and as many as two rubidium atomic clocks.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The relative times are mathematically transformed into three absolute spatial coordinates and one absolute time coordinate.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] GPS Time (GPST) is a continuous time scale and theoretically accurate to about 14 nanoseconds.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] However, most receivers lose accuracy in the interpretation of the signals and are only accurate to 100 nanoseconds.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] GPST is related to but differs from TAI (International Atomic Time) and UTC (Coordinated Universal Time).
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] GPST remains at a constant offset from TAI (TAI – GPST = 19 seconds) and like TAI does not implement leap seconds.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Periodic corrections are performed to the on-board clocks in the satellites to keep them synchronized with ground clocks.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The GPS navigation message includes the difference between GPST and UTC.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] As of July 2015, GPST is 17 seconds ahead of UTC because of the leap second added to UTC on 30 June 2015.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Receivers subtract this offset from GPS Time to calculate UTC.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The GLObal NAvigation Satellite System (GLONASS) operated by the Russian Aerospace Defence Forces provides an alternative to the Global Positioning System (GPS) system and is the second navigational system in operation with global coverage and of comparable precision.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] GLONASS Time (GLONASST) is generated by the GLONASS Central Synchroniser and is typically better than 1,000 nanoseconds.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Unlike GPS, the GLONASS time scale implements leap seconds, like UTC.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The Galileo Global Navigation Satellite System is operated by the European GNSS Agency and European Space Agency.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Galileo started offering global Early Operational Capability (EOC) on 15 December 2016, providing the third, and first non-military operated, global navigation satellite system.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] According to the European GNSS Agency, Galileo offers 30 nanoseconds timing accuracy.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The March 2018 Quarterly Performance Report by the European GNSS Service Centre reported the UTC Time Dissemination Service Accuracy was ≤ 7.6 nanoseconds, computed by accumulating samples over the previous 12 months, and exceeding the ≤ 30 ns target.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Each Galileo satellite has two passive hydrogen maser and two rubidium atomic clocks for onboard timing.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The Galileo navigation message includes the differences between GST, UTC and GPST, to promote interoperability.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In the summer of 2021, the European Union settled on a passive hydrogen maser for the second generation of Galileo satellites, starting in 2023, with an expected lifetime of 12 years per satellite.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The masers are about 2 feet long with a weight of 40 pounds.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The BeiDou-2/BeiDou-3 satellite navigation system is operated by the China National Space Administration.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] BeiDou Time (BDT) is a continuous time scale starting at 1 January 2006 at 0:00:00 UTC and is synchronised with UTC within 100 ns.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] BeiDou became operational in China in December 2011, with 10 satellites in use, and began offering services to customers in the Asia-Pacific region in December 2012.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] On 27 December 2018 the BeiDou Navigation Satellite System started to provide global services with a reported timing accuracy of 20 ns.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The final, 35th, BeiDou-3 satellite for global coverage was launched into orbit on 23 June 2020.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In April 2015, NASA announced that it planned to deploy a Deep Space Atomic Clock (DSAC), a miniaturized, ultra-precise mercury-ion atomic clock, into outer space.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] NASA said that the DSAC would be much more stable than other navigational clocks.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The clock was successfully launched on 25 June 2019, activated on 23 August 2019 and deactivated two years later on 18 September 2021.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In 2022, DARPA announced a drive to upgrade to the U.S. military timekeeping systems for greater precision over time when sensors do not have access to GPS satellites, with a plan to reach precision of 1 part in 1012.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] The Robust Optical Clock Network will balance usability and accuracy as it is developed over 4 years.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] A radio clock is a clock that automatically synchronizes itself by means of radio time signals received by a radio receiver.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Some manufacturers may label radio clocks as atomic clocks, because the radio signals they receive originate from atomic clocks.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Normal low-cost consumer-grade receivers that rely on the amplitude-modulated time signals have a practical accuracy uncertainty of ± 0.1 second.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] This is sufficient for many consumer applications.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Instrument grade time receivers provide higher accuracy.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Radio clocks incur a propagation delay of approximately 1 ms for every 300 kilometres (186 mi) of distance from the radio transmitter.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Many governments operate transmitters for timekeeping purposes.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] General relativity predicts that clocks tick slower deeper in a gravitational field, and this gravitational redshift effect has been well documented.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks are effective at testing general relativity on ever smaller scales.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] A project to observe twelve atomic clocks from 11 November 1999 to October 2014 resulted in a further demonstration that Einstein's theory of general relativity is accurate at small scales.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In 2021 a team of scientists at JILA measured the difference in the passage of time due to gravitational redshift between two layers of atoms separated by one millimeter using a strontium optical clock cooled to 100 nanokelvins with a precision of 7.6×10−21 seconds.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Given its quantum nature and the fact that time is a relativistic quantity, atomic clocks can be used to see how time is influenced by general relativity and quantum mechanics at the same time.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Atomic clocks keep accurate records of transactions between buyers and sellers to the millisecond or better, particularly in high-frequency trading.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Accurate timekeeping is needed to prevent illegal trading ahead of time, in addition to ensuring fairness to traders on the other side of the globe.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] In 2018, the then current system known as NTP is only accurate to a millisecond.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Many of the most accurate optical clocks are big and only available in large metrology labs.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Thus they are not readily useful for space-limited factories or other industrial environments that could use an atomic clock for GPS accuracy.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Researchers have designed a strontium optical lattice clock that can be moved around in an air-conditioned car trailer.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] They achieved a relative uncertainty of 7.4×10−17 compared to a stationary one.
[src:atomic-clock/atomic-clock] Manufacturers of atomic clocks in use for keeping track of UTC includes Microchip, T4Science, Anritsu, Microsemi and HP.
